y, who was appointed CEO in 1984. Both HNG and InterNorth were first-rate com-\npanies with impeccable credentials, and both were targets for hostile takeovers. In an\nattempt to avoid such takeovers, the two companies merged in 1985, and Lay became\nCEO of the new conglomerate, which took the name of Enron.\n\nSo perhaps the real story of Enron starts with the story of Kenneth Lay.\n\nKenneth Lay\n\nBorn in Missouri in 1942, Kenneth Lay was the son of respectable, down-to-earth\nparents who constantly struggled to make ends meet. At one stage in Lay’s early child-\nhood, after his parents’ feed store had gone bankrupt, Lay and his family “bounced\n\n203\n''"
